{"title_page": "Hedley Hope-Nicholson", "text_new": "'''Hedley Hope-Nicholson''' (born William Hedley Kenelm Nicholson, July 1888\u201318 July 1969), barrister and litt\u00e9rateur, and his wife Jaqueline Louise Rachel (d. 1972), daughter of Adrian Charles Francis Hope, descended from the [[Marquess of Linlithgow|Earls of Hopetoun]],<ref>Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage, 1920, pg 561</ref> were notable in English artistic and literary circles in the first half of the twentieth century.<ref>Obituary in ''The Times'' (26 July 1969, p.10). The obituary gives his age at death as \"81\".</ref> Hedley Nicholson (he joined his patronymic with that of his wife by [[deed-poll]]) counted among various eccentric hobbies a keen interest in [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] and was editor of the quarterly magazine of the [[Society of King Charles the Martyr]]. He kept a relic from the King's coffin and a piece of the shirt he wore on the scaffold in a box in the consecrated chapel in their London family home, [[More House]], in [[Tite Street]], [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]]. His other great passion was for the Russian ballet. He was the author of ''The Mindes Delight: or Variety of Memorable Matters Worthy of Observation'' (1928).\n\nJaqueline Hope-Nicholson was a [[genealogist]], heraldic artist and impassioned costumier dealing with vast outdoor pageants and innumerable amateur theatricals but her greatest interest was in the Stuart kings, largely Charles II.\n\nTheir children were the artist Mary Lauretta Jaqueline Desir\u00e9e Valentine Esm\u00e9 ('Lauretta', 1919\u20132005) who married the artist [[Jean Hugo]] in 1949 and worked as an assistant editor on the Burlington Magazine and with [[Richard Buckle]] on his publication 'Ballet'; Marie-Jaqueline Dorothea Beatrice Alexina Romaine Adriana (9 August 1922 \u2013 17 May 2010; married in 1945 war correspondent (Herbert) Maurice Lancaster and had two daughters), who compiled ''Brian Howard: Portrait of a Failure in 1968'', about [[Brian Howard (poet)|Brian Howard]]; and Charles Felix Otho Victor Gabriel John Adrian ('[[Felix Hope-Nicholson|Felix]]', 1921\u20131990), genealogist and antiquarian.\n\nAccording to the art historian and writer [[Bevis Hillier]], [[John Betjeman]] wrote a libellous couplet about Hope-Nicholson and his (at the time unusual for a man) habit of using make-up:\n\n<blockquote>\nH is for Hedley, who lives in a Place.<br>\nWhat he makes on his bottom, he spends on his face''.<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/2006/01/the-other-life-of-brian</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, James Lees-Milne, in his Diaries, gave a different account and version of the poem: \"John Betjeman quotes the following couplet composed by the [[John Davies Knatchbull Lloyd|Widow Lloyd]] about Hedley Hope-Nicholson, that painted- but delightful- old queen: \n<blockquote>\nH is for Hedley, the pride of Old Place,<br>\nWhat he earned from his bottom he spent on his face''.<ref>Diaries 1971-1983, James Lees-Milne, John Murray, 2008, p. 243</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hope-Nicholson, Hedley}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:English academics]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n\n\n{{England-academic-stub}}\n{{england-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hedley Hope-Nicholson''' (born William Hedley Kenelm Nicholson, July 1888\u201318 July 1969), barrister and litt\u00e9rateur, and his wife Jaqueline Louise Rachel (d. 1972), daughter of Adrian Charles Francis Hope, descended from the [[Marquess of Linlithgow|Earls of Hopetoun]],<ref>Debrett's Peerage, Baronetage and Knightage, 1920, pg 561</ref> were notable in English artistic and literary circles in the first half of the twentieth century.<ref>Obituary in ''The Times'' (26 July 1969, p.10). The obituary gives his age at death as \"81\".</ref> Hedley Nicholson (he joined his patronymic with that of his wife by [[deed-poll]]) counted among various eccentric hobbies a keen interest in [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]] and was editor of the quarterly magazine of the [[Society of King Charles the Martyr]]. He kept a relic from the King's coffin and a piece of the shirt he wore on the scaffold in a box in the consecrated chapel in their London family home, [[More House]], in [[Tite Street]], [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]]. His other great passion was for the Russian ballet. He was the author of ''The Mindes Delight: or Variety of Memorable Matters Worthy of Observation'' (1928).\n\nJaqueline Hope-Nicholson was a [[genealogist]], heraldic artist and impassioned costumier dealing with vast outdoor pageants and innumerable amateur theatricals but her greatest interest was in the Stuart kings, largely Charles II.\n\nTheir children were the artist Mary Lauretta Jaqueline Desir\u00e9e Valentine Esm\u00e9 ('Lauretta', 1919\u20132005) who married the artist [[Jean Hugo]] in 1949 and worked as an assistant editor on the Burlington Magazine and with [[Richard Buckle]] on his publication 'Ballet'; Marie-Jaqueline Dorothea Beatrice Alexina Romaine Adriana (9 August 1922 \u2013 17 May 2010; married in 1945 war correspondent (Herbert) Maurice Lancaster and had two daughters), who compiled ''Brian Howard: Portrait of a Failure in 1968'', about [[Brian Howard (poet)|Brian Howard]]; and Charles Felix Otho Victor Gabriel John Adrian ('[[Felix Hope-Nicholson|Felix]]', 1921\u20131990), genealogist and antiquarian.\n\nAccording to the art historian and writer [[Bevis Hillier]], [[John Betjeman]] wrote a libellous couplet about Hope-Nicholson and his (at the time unusual for a man) habit of using make-up:\n\n<blockquote>\nH is for Hedley, who lives in a Place.<br>\nWhat he makes on his bottom, he spends on his face''.<ref>https://www.spectator.co.uk/2006/01/the-other-life-of-brian</ref></blockquote>\n\nHowever, James Lees-Milne, in his Diaries, gave a different account and version of the poem: \"John Betjeman quotes the following couplet composed by the [[John Davies Knatchbull Lloyd|Widow Lloyd]] about Hedley Hope-Nicholson, that painted- but delightful- old queen: \n<blockquote>\nH is for Hedley, the pride of Old Place,<br>\nWhat he earned from his bottom he spent on his face''.<ref>Diaries 1971-1983, James Lees-Milne, John Murray, 2008, p. 243</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hope-Nicholson, Hedley}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1969 deaths]]\n[[Category:English academics]]\n[[Category:English writers]]\n\n{{England-academic-stub}}\n{{england-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hedley_Hope-Nicholson"}
{"title_page": "Heather Smith (author)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Heather Smith\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = Heather_Smith,_Australian_Author.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Heather Smith\n| native_name   =\n| native_name_lang =\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Accountant, Writer, Speaker\n| language      = \n| nationality   = Australian\n| ethnicity     = \n| religion =\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Griffith University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = [[Non-fiction]]\n| subject       = [[Business]], [[Cloud computing]]\n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = Learn MYOB in 7 Days, Learn Small Business Startup in 7 Days\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = Granddaughter of Ashley Smith\n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.heathersmithsmallbusiness.com/}}\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Heather Smith''' is an [[Australia]]n-born author,<ref>{{cite web|title=How attending conferences can build your business|url=http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/managing/blogs/enterprise/how-attending-conferences-can-build-your-business-20120329-1vzjs.html|publisher=SMH.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> chartered certified accountant,<ref>{{cite web|title=Xero For Dummies|url=http://au.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-1118572556.html|publisher=Wiley books|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> writer, speaker,<ref name=\"Smith2013ConvertXero\">{{cite book|author=Heather Smith|title=Converting to Xero from MYOB In A Day For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nfodAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|date=16 July 2013|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-57249-8|pages=65\u2013}}</ref> and small-business consultant,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ten strategies to get invoices paid promptly|url=http://businesslounge.net.au/2012/11/ten-strategies-to-get-invoices-paid-promptly/|publisher=Business Lounge|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> based in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia.\n\nShe is best known as the author of ''Xero for Dummies''<ref>{{cite web|title=Xero accounting software gets its very own Dummies book|url=http://www.brw.com.au/p/professions/xero_accounting_software_gets_its_r1rrKAOGULogYQrpZnoUUP|publisher=BRW.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> series and ''Learn Small Business Start Up in 7 Days''.<ref>{{cite web|title=PreneurCast093: Conversation with Heather Smith|url=http://preneurmarketing.com/preneurcast/preneurcast093-conversation-with-heather-smith/|publisher=The Preneurcast, 23 March 2013|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> She was personally approached by Xero's co-founder [[Rod Drury]] to write ''Xero for Dummies''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Q&A with Heather Smith on issues facing businesses today|url=https://community.optus.com.au/t5/Optus-Business-Insights-Blog/Our-Q-amp-A-with-Heather-Smith-on-issues-facing-businesses-today/ba-p/45998|website=The Optus Business Insights Blog|publisher=Optus|accessdate=18 August 2014|ref=SmithOptusQandA}}</ref>\n\nSmith is also a certified advisor for both [[Xero (software)|Xero]]<ref name=\"Smith2013XeroDum\">{{cite book|author=Heather Smith|title=Xero For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H-mM3EYEndkC&pg=PP1|date=13 May 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-57253-5|pages=1\u2013}}</ref> and [[MYOB (company)|MYOB]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five big tips and mistakes to avoid with cloud accounting|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/finance/32556-five-big-tips-and-mistakes-to-avoid-with-cloud-accounting.html#|publisher=Smart Company.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nSmith is a Fellow of the [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]]. She has a Bachelor of Commerce from [[Griffith University]]. She is one of the mentors at River City Labs, a non profit organisation aiming to promote high-tech start up businesses in Brisbane and surrounding regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Mentors|url=http://www.rivercitylabs.net/about/|website=River City Labs|accessdate=18 August 2014|ref=SmithRiverCityLabs}}</ref> She performs a similar role at the Sunshine Coast Innovation Centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mentor Panel|url=http://www.innovationcentre.com.au/mentor-panel|website=Sunshine Coast Innovation Centre|accessdate=18 August 2014 |ref=SmithSunshineCoastInnov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318214845/http://www.innovationcentre.com.au/mentor-panel|archivedate=18 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n* Xero for Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=111857253X]\n* Learn Small Business Startup in 7 Days [https://books.google.com/books?id=36VDgvPv-7YC]\n* Learn MYOB in 7 Days [https://books.google.com/books?id=Z_kbViMs8LUC]\n* Mastering Australian Payroll with Xero In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572459]\n* Converting to Xero from MYOB In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572491]\n* Getting the Most Out of Xero In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572491]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Heather}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n[[Category:Griffith University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Heather Smith\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image         = Heather_Smith,_Australian_Author.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Heather Smith\n| native_name   =\n| native_name_lang =\n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Accountant, Writer, Speaker\n| language      = \n| nationality   = Australian\n| ethnicity     = \n| religion =\n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = [[Griffith University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = [[Non-fiction]]\n| subject       = [[Business]], [[Cloud computing]]\n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = Learn MYOB in 7 Days, Learn Small Business Startup in 7 Days\n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = Granddaughter of Ashley Smith\n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.heathersmithsmallbusiness.com/}}\n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Heather Smith''' is an [[Australia]]n-born author,<ref>{{cite web|title=How attending conferences can build your business|url=http://www.smh.com.au/small-business/managing/blogs/enterprise/how-attending-conferences-can-build-your-business-20120329-1vzjs.html|publisher=SMH.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> chartered certified accountant,<ref>{{cite web|title=Xero For Dummies|url=http://au.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-1118572556.html|publisher=Wiley books|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> writer, speaker,<ref name=\"Smith2013ConvertXero\">{{cite book|author=Heather Smith|title=Converting to Xero from MYOB In A Day For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nfodAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|date=16 July 2013|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-57249-8|pages=65\u2013}}</ref> and small-business consultant,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ten strategies to get invoices paid promptly|url=http://businesslounge.net.au/2012/11/ten-strategies-to-get-invoices-paid-promptly/|publisher=Business Lounge|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> based in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia.\n\nShe is best known as the author of ''Xero for Dummies''<ref>{{cite web|title=Xero accounting software gets its very own Dummies book|url=http://www.brw.com.au/p/professions/xero_accounting_software_gets_its_r1rrKAOGULogYQrpZnoUUP|publisher=BRW.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> series and ''Learn Small Business Start Up in 7 Days''.<ref>{{cite web|title=PreneurCast093: Conversation with Heather Smith|url=http://preneurmarketing.com/preneurcast/preneurcast093-conversation-with-heather-smith/|publisher=The Preneurcast, 23 March 2013|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> She was personally approached by Xero's co-founder [[Rod Drury]] to write ''Xero for Dummies''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Q&A with Heather Smith on issues facing businesses today|url=https://community.optus.com.au/t5/Optus-Business-Insights-Blog/Our-Q-amp-A-with-Heather-Smith-on-issues-facing-businesses-today/ba-p/45998|website=The Optus Business Insights Blog|publisher=Optus|accessdate=18 August 2014|ref=SmithOptusQandA}}</ref>\n\nSmith is also a certified advisor for both [[Xero (software)|Xero]]<ref name=\"Smith2013XeroDum\">{{cite book|author=Heather Smith|title=Xero For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H-mM3EYEndkC&pg=PP1|date=13 May 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-57253-5|pages=1\u2013}}</ref> and [[MYOB (company)|MYOB]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Five big tips and mistakes to avoid with cloud accounting|url=http://www.smartcompany.com.au/finance/32556-five-big-tips-and-mistakes-to-avoid-with-cloud-accounting.html#|publisher=Smart Company.com.au|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nSmith is a Fellow of the [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]]. She has a Bachelor of Commerce from [[Griffith University]]. She is one of the mentors at River City Labs, a non profit organisation aiming to promote high-tech start up businesses in Brisbane and surrounding regions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Mentors|url=http://www.rivercitylabs.net/about/|website=River City Labs|accessdate=18 August 2014|ref=SmithRiverCityLabs}}</ref> She performs a similar role at the Sunshine Coast Innovation Centre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mentor Panel|url=http://www.innovationcentre.com.au/mentor-panel|website=Sunshine Coast Innovation Centre|accessdate=18 August 2014 |ref=SmithSunshineCoastInnov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318214845/http://www.innovationcentre.com.au/mentor-panel|archivedate=18 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n* Xero for Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=111857253X]\n* Learn Small Business Startup in 7 Days [https://books.google.com/books?id=36VDgvPv-7YC]\n* Learn MYOB in 7 Days [https://books.google.com/books?id=Z_kbViMs8LUC]\n* Mastering Australian Payroll with Xero In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572459]\n* Converting to Xero from MYOB In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572491]\n* Getting the Most Out of Xero In A Day For Dummies [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1118572491]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Heather}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n[[Category:Griffith University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_Smith_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Ron Haddrick", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian cricketer and actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Ron Haddrick\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|sep=,|AM|MBE}}\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| birth_name  = Ronald Norman Haddrick\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1929|4|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|2|11|1929|4|9}}\n| death_place = [[Sydney, New South Wales]], Australia\n| nationality = [[Australian]]\n| occupation = {{hlist|Film and television actor|theatre performer and stage manager|radio actor and presenter|voice artist|first-class cricketer}}\n| years_active = 1946\u20132019\n| spouse     = Lorraine n\u00e9e Quigley\n| children   = Lynette Haddrick<br>[[Greg Haddrick]]\n}}\n'''Ronald Norman Haddrick''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AM|MBE}} (9 April 1929 &ndash; 11 February 2020)  was an [[Australian]] cricketer, theatre performer, stage manager, and radio and television actor and presenter. In 2012, he received the [[Equity Ensemble Awards|Actors Equity Lifetime Achievement Award]] for his long and distinguished career in those media.<ref>[https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/128273/ron-haddrick-am-mbe/?r=https://tributes.smh.com.au/obituaries/smh-au/search/?Query=RON%20%20HADDRICK%20AM%20MBE SMH Deaths Ron Haddrick AM MBE 9.4.1929 - 11.2.2020] Retrieved 21 February 2020.</ref><ref>[https://medium.com/the-equity-magazine/leading-man-in-art-and-life-e85a4bf68d6b LEADING MAN \u2014 IN ART AND LIFE] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref> At the time Australian playwright [[David Williamson]] said, \u201cRon Haddrick was chosen for two reasons. He\u2019s a great actor, definitely one of the greatest of his generation, and also a great human being who has enriched the lives of countless Australians through his acting. He has also enriched the lives of many of us who work in the theatre because of his dedication and palpable decency.\u201d Actor [[John Bell (Australian actor)|John Bell]] in presenting the award said his \u201ccareer has been extraordinary ... he is undoubtedly one of the leading lights in the Australian acting industry and he is much loved, admired and respected, because of both his professionalism and his good nature.\u201d <ref>[http://m.theage.com.au/entertainment/theatre/lifetime-award-shows-its-not-just-a-stage-hes-going-through-20121119-29m1q.html \"Lifetime Award shows that its not just a stage he is going through\"] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref> On news of his death [[Bell Shakespeare]] said: \u201ca legend of Australian theatre ... it was a privilege to have him grace our stage\u201d <ref>[https://m.facebook.com/BellShakespeareCo/photos/a.120884807987922/2690700617672982/?type=3&eid=ARAx7UNg4HVNgugNNz5MDRuOEhgG7JM7O1gfzszNztRpXEgQ5y7GtO-zx6pOQ0kMzJLdbOPceW5Ts2Q2 Vale Ron Haddrick] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHaddrick was born in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], the only son of Olive May (n\u00e9e Gibson) and Alexander Norman Haddrick.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/98/Ron-Haddrick.html \"Ron Haddrick Biography (1929\u2013)\"]. Film Reference. Retrieved December 22, 2013.</ref> Haddrick's wife, Lorraine, received the [[Australian Sports Medal]] in 2000 for her \"outstanding dedication to athletics as a volunteer official for 32 years\".<ref>[https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/981997 It's an Honour] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref> They have two children: [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]] graduate Lynette Haddrick<ref>[https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/contributor/227105 Austage] Retrieved 28 May 2015.</ref> and screenwriter and producer [[Greg Haddrick]], and three grandchildren, Taya, Milly and  Jack Haddrick.\n\n==Cricket career==\nAs a sportsman, Haddrick played [[first-class cricket]] during the 1950s, representing [[South Australian cricket team|South Australia]] on three occasions in the [[Sheffield Shield]] competition.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/player/5783.html Crininfo] retrieved 28 May 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|magazine=Filmink|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/good-sports-australian-athletes-act/|title=Good Sports: Australian Athletes Who Act|date=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n==Professional acting career==\n===Theatre===\nHaddrick first appeared on the stage in 1946 at the [[Tivoli circuit|Adelaide Tivoli Theatre]]. Later, he was invited to join the Stratford Memorial Theatre (now the [[Royal Shakespeare Theatre]]). During five seasons in [[Stratford-upon-Avon]] he performed with [[Laurence Olivier]], [[Vivien Leigh]], [[John Gielgud]], [[Peggy Ashcroft]] and [[Michael Redgrave]]. On his return to Sydney, roles followed with the [[Australian Elizabethan Theatre Trust|Trust Players]], and when the [[Old Tote Theatre Company]] formed, Haddrick played in over forty productions.\n===Radio and television===\nHaddrick has worked extensively in radio and TV throughout his career, notably for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]. He made an early television appearance in the 1960 television play ''[[Close to the Roof]]''. He had his first starring TV role as Dr. William Redfern in ''[[The Outcasts (1961 TV series)|The Outcasts]]'', later appearing as the alien \"Adam Suisse\" in [[G K Saunders]]' pioneering children's science fiction series ''[[The Stranger (Australian TV series)|The Stranger]]'', broadcast on the ABC in 1964\u201365. In 1969, he voiced Ebenezer Scrooge for an Australian produced ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'', giving way to more work along the same lines in the Australian animation field in 1977 with a shorter version of Jules Verne's ''[[Journey to the Center of the Earth]]''.\n===Narrator===\nHe has also narrated six audio books of the British children's TV series ''[[Thomas the Tank Engine & Friends]]'' released by ABC For Kids which were written by [[Christopher Awdry]] and illustrated by Ken Stott.\n\nHaddrick is also known for having narrated all audio books of the Australian children's/young adult fantasy book series ''[[Deltora Quest (series)|Deltora Quest]]'' written by [[Emily Rodda]].\n===Selected works===\nOther stage work in the '70s and \u201880s included major roles for [[Sydney Theatre Company]], [[State Theatre Company of South Australia]] and [[Queensland Theatre Company]] in classics and new Australian plays, including extensive seasons of the [[Nimrod Theatre Company]] production of ''[[The Club (play)|The Club]]''. Haddrick received two of the now defunct \"Sydney Theatre Critics Circle Awards\" for his performances in ''[[Long Day's Journey into Night]]'' and ''[[I'm Not Rappaport]]''. The '90s saw him in many roles for [http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/marian_street_theatre_community_theatre_and_northside_theatre Marian Street Theatre] and the STC including his [[King Lear]] and his much loved Wacka Dawson in ''[[The One Day of the Year]]''. Haddrick has appeared in Australian-made television from ''[[Certain Women (television series)|Certain Women]]'' and [[Heartbreak High]] to ''[[Farscape]]'' and in numerous feature films. Haddrick also played on ''[[The Lost Islands]]'' playing the tyrant \"Q\", a 200-year-old ruler. On radio, he has performed in hundreds of dramas, documentaries, special features and was frequently heard reading poetry for the [[ABC Radio and Regional Content|ABC]].<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/98/Ron-Haddrick.html Ron Haddrick Biography (1929\u2013)] Retrieved 28 May 2015.</ref>\n\n==Haddrick and Cracknell==\nIn 1960 Haddrick appeared at the [[Adelaide Festival of Arts]] in a production of ''[[Murder in the Cathedral]]'' in [[Bonython Hall]]. It marked the start of a long working partnership between Haddrick and [[Ruth Cracknell]]. In 1970 they performed in [[Sophocles]]' ''[[Oedipus Rex]]''. It was directed for the Old Tote in Sydney by Sir [[Tyrone Guthrie]] and toured widely.  In 1973, Haddrick, Ruth Cracknell, [[Gordon Chater]] and [[Garry McDonald]] appeared at the Australian Theatre in Newtown in a miscellany called Aurora Australis. They were in the Old Tote's production of David Williamson's ''[[What If You Died Tomorrow?]]'' in 1974 and it toured Australia and played in London at the [[Comedy Theatre]]. In the late 1970s they were in two Peter Williams' productions at the [[Theatre Royal, Sydney]], ''[[Bedroom Farce]]'' and ''[[The Gin Game]]''. In 1983 Haddrick and Cracknell played the theatrical Mr and Mrs Crummles in [[Richard Wherrett]]\u2019s production of David Edgar's two-part [[Charles Dickens|Dickens]] marathon, ''[[The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby]]'' for the [[Sydney Theatre Company]]. This played at the Theatre Royal in Sydney and the State Theatre in Melbourne. In 1990 they were reunited in [[A.R. Gurney]]'s ''[[Love Letters]]'' for the Sydney Theatre Company.<ref>[https://liveperformance.com.au/hof-profile/ruth-cracknell-am-1925-2002/ Ruth Cracknell AM 1925 \u2013 2002] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHaddrick died at home on 11 February 2020. A memorial service was held at The Parade Theatre at [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]] on 1 March 2020, where speakers included actor and director John Bell and former Australian cricket captain [[Ian Chappell]].<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/national/cricketer-and-actor-who-worked-with-the-biggest-names-in-theatre-20200302-p545xy.html SMH Obituary \u2013 Cricketer and actor who worked with the biggest names in theatre] Retrieved 3 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/ron-haddrick-one-of-the-great-actors-of-his-generation/news-story/2bcb07a758001ee75640865d2074a0bc A gentleman, and one of the great actors of his generation] Retrieved 3 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n*In 1974 he was made a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (Civil Division) \u2013 For services to the Arts.<ref>[https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/1088831 It\u2019s an Honour] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref>\n*In 1977 he received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]].\n*In 2012 he was awarded an [[Equity Ensemble Awards|Actors Equity Lifetime Achievement Award]] \u2013 for a lifetime combining a phenomenal career with generous leadership and selfless mentorship presented by [[Actors Equity of Australia|Actors Equity Australia]].<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/theatre/lifetime-award-shows-its-not-just-a-stage-hes-going-through-20121119-29m1q.html Ron Haddrick honoured with Lifetime Achievement Award] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref>\n*In 2013 he was made a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] (General Division) \u2013 For significant service to the performing arts as an actor and narrator.<ref>[https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/1088831 It's an Honour] Retrieved 14 February 2020.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1955|| ''Othello'' (TV movie) ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Close to the Roof]]'' (TV movie) || Joe Collon\n|-\n|1961|| ''[[The Outcasts (Australian TV series)|The Outcasts]]''  (TV mini-series) || Dr. William Redfern\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[Reunion Day (TV movie)|Reunion Day]]''  (TV  movie) || Dave Rubin\n|-\n|1962||  ''[[The Case of Private Hamp]]''  (TV movie) || Padre\n|-\n|1962|| ''The Taming of the Schew'' || Petrecio\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[A Dead Secret]]'' (TV movie) ||\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[Jonah (TV series)|Jonah]]'' (TV series) || Governor\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[The Tempest (1963 film)|The Tempest]]'' (TV movie) ||\n|-\n|1963\u20131964|| ''[[Tribunal (TV series)|Tribunal]]'' (TV series) || \u2013 Marcus Brutes<br />- John Brown\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[The Stranger (Australian TV series)|The Stranger]]'' (TV series) || \u2013 The Stranger<br />- Adam Suisse\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[The Late Edwina Black]]'' (TV movie) || Gregory Black\n|-\n|1965|| ''The Big Killing'' || Gavin Cole\n|-\n|1965||