{"title_page": "Robin Hood (2010 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2010 adventure movie by Ridley Scott}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Robin Hood\n| image          = Robin Hood 2010 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ridley Scott]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Ridley Scott\n* [[Brian Grazer]]\n* Russell Crowe\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Brian Helgeland]]\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Brian Helgeland\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Ethan Reiff]]\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Cyrus Voris]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Russell Crowe]]\n* [[Cate Blanchett]]\n* [[William Hurt]]\n* [[Mark Strong]]\n* [[Mark Addy]]\n* [[Oscar Isaac]]\n* [[Danny Huston]]\n* [[Eileen Atkins]]\n* [[Max von Sydow]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Marc Streitenfeld]]\n| cinematography = [[John Mathieson (cinematographer)|John Mathieson]]\n| editing        = [[Pietro Scalia]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Imagine Entertainment]]\n* [[Relativity Media]]\n* [[Scott Free Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|05|12|United Kingdom/Ireland|2010|05|14|North America|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 140 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2010/film/markets-festivals/robin-hood-1117942702/|title=Review: 'Robin Hood'|last=Chang|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 May 2010|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>\n| language       = English<br />French\n| budget         = $200 million<ref name=\"Fritz (2010)\">{{cite news |last=Fritz |first=Ben |title=''First Look: 'Robin Hood' wobbly in U.S. but hits target overseas'' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=16 May 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/05/robin-hood-wobbly-in-us-but-hits-target-overseas.html |accessdate= 12 September 2010}}</ref>\n| gross          = $321.7 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nottingham.htm | title=Robin Hood (2010) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Robin Hood''''' is a 2010 [[Epic film|epic]] [[Historical film|historical drama film]] based on the [[Robin Hood]] legend, directed by [[Ridley Scott]] and starring [[Russell Crowe]], [[Cate Blanchett]], [[William Hurt]], [[Mark Strong]], [[Mark Addy]], [[Oscar Isaac]], [[Danny Huston]], [[Eileen Atkins]], and [[Max von Sydow]]. It was released in 12 countries on 12 May 2010, including the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Ireland]] and was also the opening film at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]] the same day. It was released in a further 23 countries the following day, among them [[Australia]], and an additional 17 countries on 14 May 2010, among them the [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=IMDbReleaseDates>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0955308/releaseinfo IMDb: ''Release dates for Robin Hood'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> The film received mixed reviews and grossed $321.7 million against its $200 million budget, thus being considered a box office disappointment.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Anchor|Premise}}\nIn the year 1199, [[Robin Hood|Robin Longstride]] serves as a common [[archery|archer]] in the army of [[Richard I of England|King Richard the Lionheart]]. A veteran of [[Third Crusade|Richard's crusade]], he now takes part in the siege of [[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Chalus Castle]]. Disillusioned and war-weary, he gives a frank but unflattering appraisal of the King's conduct when the King asks his opinion, and Robin and his comrades\u2014archers [[Alan-a-Dale|Allan A'Dayle]] and [[Will Scarlett]] and soldier [[Little John]]\u2014find themselves in the [[stocks]].\n\nWhen the King is slain during an attack on the castle, Robin and his men decide to free themselves and desert. They come across an ambush of the English royal guard by Godfrey, an English knight who has conspired with [[Philip II of France|King Philip of France]] to assassinate King Richard. After chasing Godfrey away, Robin decides to take advantage of the situation by having his men impersonate the dead English knights to return to England. Before they depart to sail across the Channel, Robin promises one of the dying knights, Sir Robert Loxley, to return his sword to his father in [[Nottingham]].\n\nAwaking to find his party in the Thames estuary, Robin must continue to assume the identity of Loxley to inform the royal family of King Richard's death. He witnesses the coronation of [[John, King of England|King John]], who orders the collection of harsh new taxes and dispatches Godfrey to the [[Northern England|North]] to do so\u2014unaware that Godfrey will instead use French troops to stir up unrest and to prepare for King Philip to invade England.\n\nRobin and his companions head to Nottingham, where Loxley's elderly and blind father, Sir Walter, asks him to continue impersonating his son to prevent the Crown from seizing the Loxley family lands. Loxley's widow, [[Maid Marian|Lady Marian]], is initially cold toward Robin, but warms to him when he and his men merrily recover [[tithe]]d grain for the townsfolk to plant.\n\nGodfrey's actions incite the northern barons, who march to meet King John. Speaking now for Sir Walter, Robin proposes that King John agree to a [[Charter of the Forest|charter of rights]] to ensure the rights of every Englishman and to unite his country. Having realised Godfrey's deception, and knowing he must meet the French invasion with an army, the King agrees. Meanwhile, French marauders plunder Nottingham. Robin and the northern barons arrive to stop Godfrey's men, but not before Godfrey has slain the blind Sir Walter.\n\nAs the main French expeditionary force begins its invasion of England on a beach below the [[cliffs of Dover]], Robin leads the now united English army against them. In the midst of the battle, Robin duels with Godfrey, who attempts to kill Marian and flees until Robin finally kills him with an arrow from afar. King Philip realises that his plan to divide England has failed and calls off his invasion. When King John sees the French surrendering to Robin instead of to himself, he senses a threat to his power. In London, King John reneges on his promise to sign the charter and declares Robin an [[outlaw]] to be hunted throughout the kingdom. The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] announces the decree, and Robin and his men flee to [[Sherwood Forest]] with the orphans of Nottingham. Marian narrates their new life in the greenwood, noting that they live in equality as they right the many wrongs in the kingdom of King John. \"And so the legend begins.\"\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Russell Crowe]] as [[Robin Hood|Robin Longstride]]\n* [[Cate Blanchett]] as [[Maid Marian|Marian Loxley]]\n* [[William Hurt]] as [[William Marshal, 1st Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Borys Kit |title=William Hurt jousting for Robin Hood role |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=12 April 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3iddc0608768893d1e82e7cae7eec09ccd |accessdate=13 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414080023/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3iddc0608768893d1e82e7cae7eec09ccd |archivedate=14 April 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Mark Strong]] as Sir Godfrey, Prince John's henchman\n* [[Mark Addy]] as [[Friar Tuck]]\n* [[Oscar Isaac]] as [[John, King of England|Prince John]], the younger brother of King Richard\n* [[Danny Huston]] as [[Richard I of England|King Richard the Lionheart]]\n* [[Eileen Atkins]] as [[Eleanor of Aquitaine]], King Richard and Prince John's mother\n* [[Max von Sydow]] as Sir Walter Loxley of Peper Harow\n* [[Kevin Durand]] as [[Little John]]<ref name=\"trio\">{{cite journal|first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Trio join Ridley Scott's Robin Hood film |journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=9 March 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ia82652ffac56b32e4e4fe4b83a847fe8 |accessdate=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311043113/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ia82652ffac56b32e4e4fe4b83a847fe8 |archivedate=11 March 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Scott Grimes]] as [[Will Scarlet]]\n* [[Matthew Macfadyen]] as the [[Sheriff of Nottingham]]<ref>{{cite news | author = Peter Sciretta | title = Ridley Scott Casts Matthew Macfadyen as The Sheriff of Nottingham in Robin Hood | work = SlashFilm | date = 24 April 2009 | url = http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/04/24/ridley-scott-casts-matthew-macfadyen-as-the-sheriff-of-nottingham-in-robin-hood/ | archive-url = https://archive.is/20120911055743/http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/04/24/ridley-scott-casts-matthew-macfadyen-as-the-sheriff-of-nottingham-in-robin-hood/ | url-status=dead | archive-date = 11 September 2012 | accessdate = 24 April 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Alan Doyle]] as [[Alan-a-Dale|Allan A'Dayle]]<ref name=\"trio\" />\n* [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] as [[Isabella of Angoul\u00eame]], wife of Prince John and the French king's niece\n* [[Jonathan Zacca\u00ef]] as [[Philip II of France|King Philip of France]]\n* [[Douglas Hodge]] as Sir Robert Loxley\n* [[Robert Pugh]] as Baron Baldwin\n* [[Gerard McSorley]] as [[Walter Fitz Robert|Baron FitzRobert]]\n* [[Simon McBurney]] as Father Tancred \n* [[Mark Lewis Jones]] as Thomas Longstride, Robin's father\n* [[Denis Menochet]] as Adhemar, the aide to the French King\n* [[Jessica Raine]] as [[Isabel, Countess of Gloucester|Isabel of Gloucester]], John's first wife\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2007, [[Universal Studios]] and [[Brian Grazer]]'s [[Imagine Entertainment]] acquired a [[spec script]] written by Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris, creators of the TV series ''[[Sleeper Cell (TV series)|Sleeper Cell]]''. Their script portrayed a more sympathetic [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] and less virtuous [[Robin Hood]], who becomes involved in a love triangle with [[Maid Marian|Lady Marian]]. The writers received a seven-figure deal for the purchase. Actor [[Russell Crowe]] was cast into the role of Robin Hood with a fee of $20&nbsp;million against 20% of the gross.<ref name=flies>{{cite journal | first=Michael | last=Fleming |author2=Diane Garrett | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117958414.html | title=Universal flies with Crowe | journal=Variety | date=31 January 2007 | accessdate=30 April 2007 }}</ref> The following April, [[Ridley Scott]] was hired to direct ''Nottingham''.<ref name=set>{{cite journal | first=Michael | last=Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963977.html | title=Scott set for 'Nottingham' | journal=Variety | date=29 April 2007 | accessdate=30 April 2007 }}</ref> He had attempted to get rights for himself and [[20th Century Fox]], but had previously collaborated with Grazer on ''[[American Gangster (film)|American Gangster]]'' and signed on as director rather than producer.<ref name=\"romp\" /> Scott was not a fan of previous film versions of Robin Hood, saying \"the best, frankly, was [[Mel Brooks]]'s ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights|Men in Tights]]'', because [[Cary Elwes]] was quite a comic\".<ref name=\"cheese\">{{cite news|date=9 November 2008|first= Garth|last=Pearce|title= Russell Crowe to toughen up Robin Hood|work=[[The Times]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5114486.ece|quote=I am trying to think of the last good one,\" said Scott. \"Errol Flynn? A bit cheesy? A big cheese. God bless him. Kevin Costner? In the wig, you mean? The one I thought was the best, frankly, was Mel Brooks's Men in Tights, because Cary Elwes [who played Robin] was quite a comic. <!-- quote needed, link very likely to become unavailable -->| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5q2qBqXSq?url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5114486.ece|archivedate=27 May 2010|accessdate=11 November 2008|url-status=dead|location=London}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nScott's dissatisfaction with the script led him to delay filming, and during 2008 it was rewritten into a story about Robin Hood becoming an outlaw; at one point Crowe was even being considered for a dual role as both Robin and the Sheriff. Scott dropped the latter notion and ''Nottingham'' was retitled to reflect the more traditional angle.\n\nIn June, screenwriter [[Brian Helgeland]] was hired to rewrite the script by Reiff and Voris.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Borys|last=Kit|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i07e0f44f77790770427fb5561f94cf24|title=Helgeland new sheriff of 'Nottingham'|journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=5 June 2007|accessdate=5 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607164119/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i07e0f44f77790770427fb5561f94cf24 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=7 June 2007}}</ref> Producer Marc Shmuger explained Scott had a different interpretation of the story from \"the script, [which] had the sheriff of Nottingham as a ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]''-style forensics investigator\".<ref name=\"romp\">{{cite news|first=Patrick|last=Goldstein|title='Nottingham': Will Russell Crowe ever romp in Sherwood Forest?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=7 August 2008|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2008/08/nottingham-will.html|accessdate=7 August 2008}}</ref> Scott elaborated the script, portraying the Sheriff of Nottingham as being [[Richard I of England|Richard the Lionheart]]'s right-hand man, who returns to England to serve [[John of England|Prince John]] after Richard's assassination. Though Scott felt John \"was actually pretty smart, he got a bad rap because he introduced taxation so he's the bad guy in this\", and the Sheriff would have been torn between the \"two wrongs\" of a corrupt king and an outlaw inciting anarchy.<ref>{{cite news | first=Shawn | last=Adler | url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2007/10/22/grazer-calls-scotts-nottingham-the-gladiator-of-robin-hood-movies/ | title=Grazer Calls Scott's 'Nottingham' The 'Gladiator' of Robin Hood Movies | work=MTV Movies Blog | date=22 October 2007 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref> Locations were sought in North East England including [[Alnwick Castle]], [[Bamburgh Castle]], and [[Kielder Forest]]. A portion of filming was intended to take place in [[Northumberland]]. As a result of the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|WGA strike]], production was put on hold.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/Sir-Ridley-Scott-puts-big.3662334.jp | title=Sir Ridley Scott puts big budget movie on hold | work=[[Shields Gazette]] | publisher=[[Johnston Press]] | date=10 January 2008 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref> Scott sought to begin production in 2008 for a release in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | first=Lawrie | last=Masterson | url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23005986-5009160,00.html | title=An alliance to Crowe about | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | date=5 January 2008 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFilming was scheduled to begin in August in [[Sherwood Forest]] if the [[2008 Screen Actors Guild strike]] did not take place,<ref>{{cite news | first = Claudia | last = Eller |author2=Richard Verrier  | title = Strike threat creates a suspense drama for Hollywood | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 24 June 2008 | url = http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-actor24-2008jun24,0,4147025.story | accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref> for release on 26 November 2009. By July, filming was delayed,<ref>{{cite journal | first=Gregg | last=Kilday | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3if7b717939831cbe23d5f5d7875615784 | title=Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham' hits delay | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=27 July 2008 | accessdate=26 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080727135443/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3if7b717939831cbe23d5f5d7875615784 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 July 2008}}</ref> and playwright Paul Webb was hired to rewrite the script.<ref name=\"romp\" /> The film was moved to 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|title='Wolfman,' 'Nottingham' delayed|journal=Variety|date=10 December 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997153.html |accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref> The Sheriff of Nottingham's character was then merged with Robin.<ref>{{cite news|first=Josh|last=Horowitz|title=BREAKING: Russell Crowe Will Play Robin Hood AND The Sheriff In Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham'|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=27 September 2008|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/09/27/breaking-russell-crowe-will-play-robin-hood-and-the-sheriff-in-ridley-scotts-nottingham/|accessdate=28 September 2008}}</ref> Scott explained Robin \"has to retire to the forest to resume his name Robin. So he was momentarily the Sheriff of Nottingham.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Simon|last=Reynolds|title=\nScott explains Crowe's 'Nottingham' role|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=11 November 2008|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/a135277/scott-explains-crowes-nottingham-role.html|accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> Hedgeland returned to rewrite, adding an opening where Robin witnesses the Sheriff dying in battle, and takes over his identity.<ref name=\"confusion\">{{cite news|first=Josh|last=Horowitz|title=Brian Grazer Reveals 'Nottingham' Plot Points, Sets Record Straight on Russell Crowe Confusion|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=1 December 2008|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/12/01/brian-grazer-reveals-nottingham-plot-points-sets-record-straight-on-russell-crowe-confusion/|accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> Scott chose to begin filming in February 2009 in forests around London, having discovered many trees which had not been [[pollarding|pollarded]].<ref name=\"cheese\" /> Scott was also pleased that the {{convert|200|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[Nottinghamshire]] set that was built during 2008 had aged into the landscape.<ref>{{cite news|first=Christine|last=Sams|title=An epic of merrymen|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=1 February 2009}}</ref> By February 2009, Scott revealed ''Nottingham'' had become his version of ''Robin Hood'', as he had become dissatisfied with the idea of Robin starting as the Sheriff.<ref name=\"french\">{{cite news|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/02/17/exclusive-ridley-scott-reveals-new-name-for-nottingham-and-its-back-to-basics/|title=Ridley Scott Reveals New Name For 'Nottingham' And It's Back To Basics|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=17 February 2009|first=Larry|last=Carroll|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n| title = Filming locations\n| lines = 5\n| width = 250\n|File:Bourne Wood Movie Castle.jpg|alt1=Mock castle at the Bourne Wood at the end of filming, showing the burnt-out castle gate|Mock castle ([[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Castle Chalus]] in the film) at [[Bourne Wood]] at the end of filming, showing the burnt-out castle gate, Bourne Wood, Farnham, Surrey, 8 August 2009. {{coord|51|11|26.31|N|0|46|39.01|W|region:GB_scale:5000|display=inline}}\n|File:Bourne Wood Castle Gate.JPG|alt2=Burnt out castle gate and battering ram|Burnt out gate of mock castle and battering ram (nicknamed 'Rosie'), [[Bourne Wood]], Farnham, Surrey, 8 August 2009.\n|File:Robin Hood filming at Freshwater West.jpg|alt3=Filming the fight scenes on the beach|Filming the fight scenes on the beach, Freshwater West, Pembrokeshire, Wales, 23 June 2009. {{coord|51|39|31.90|N|5|3|52.23|W|region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline}}\n|File:Robin Hood filming at Freshwater West 2.jpg|alt4=The beach filming|The beach filming, Freshwater West, Pembrokeshire, Wales, 23 June 2009.\n}}\nFilming began on 30 March 2009.<ref name=\"pressrelease\">{{cite news|title=Ridley Scott's Robin Hood film begins production|work=In Contention|format=Press release|date=24 March 2009|url=http://www.incontention.com/?p=4917|accessdate=24 March 2009}}</ref> In June and July, the crew filmed at [[Freshwater West]], in [[Pembrokeshire]], Wales.<ref>{{cite news|title=Extras queue for Robin Hood roles|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=9 May 2009|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8041103.stm|accessdate=10 May 2009}}</ref> The arrival of the dead king's cog (boat), accompanied by Robin and his men, at the Tower of London was filmed at Virginia Water, where a partial mock-up of the Tower was built. Extensive scenes from the film were filmed on the [[Ashridge Estate]], [[Little Gaddesden]], on the [[Hertfordshire]]/[[Buckinghamshire]] border.<ref>{{cite news|title=How the National Trust came to the aid of Robin Hood |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] |date=9 May 2009 |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-news/w-latest_news/w-news-how-the-national-trust-came-to-the-aid-of-robin-hood.htm |accessdate=10 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222033551/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-news/w-latest_news/w-news-how-the-national-trust-came-to-the-aid-of-robin-hood.htm |archivedate=22 February 2010 }}</ref> Filming of the siege of [[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Castle Chalus]] took place at the [[Bourne Wood]] at [[Farnham]], Surrey during July and August.<ref name=SurreyLife>{{cite web | title=Surrey Film Locations | url=http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/surrey-film-locations-2505/ | work=Surrey Life | accessdate=1 June 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226070622/http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/surrey-film-locations-2505/ | archivedate=26 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Filming also took place at [[Dovedale]] near [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Russell Crowe in Ashbourne|publisher=BBC Derby|date=5 August 2009|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/derby/content/articles/2009/08/05/russell_crowe_in_ashbourne_2009_feature.shtml|accessdate=5 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[battering ram]] used during the filming at the Bourne Wood in Surrey, which was nicknamed 'Rosie' by the film crew and is worth [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]60,000, was donated by Russell Crowe to a [[Scotland|Scottish]] charity, the [[The Clanranald Trust for Scotland|Clanranald Trust]] to be used for battle re-enactments at a fort named [[Duncarron]], built in a forest near the [[Carron Valley Reservoir]] in [[North Lanarkshire]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Charlie|first=Allan|title=Russell Crowe Helps a friend with a cause|url=http://www.clanranald.org/cln1/the-news/31-duncarron-news/111-russell-crowe-helps-a-friend-with-a-cause|publisher=The Clanranald Trust website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019154730/http://www.clanranald.org/cln1/the-news/31-duncarron-news/111-russell-crowe-helps-a-friend-with-a-cause|archivedate=19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen interviewed in November 2008, Strong stated his character of Sir Godfrey was originally called Conrad and was based on [[Guy of Gisbourne]]. He described the original character as having blond hair and a disfigurement from being struck by a crossbow bolt.<ref>{{cite web | first = Simon | last = Reynolds | title = Strong joins Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham' | work = [[Digital Spy]] | date = 10 November 2008 | url = http://fame.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/a135178/strong-joins-ridley-scotts-nottingham.html | accessdate = 11 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on 12 May 2010 in 12 countries, including the United Kingdom and Ireland, and was also the opening film at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]] the same day. It was released in a further 23 countries the following day, among them Australia, and an additional 17 countries on 14 May 2010, among them the United States and Canada. It was thus released in 52 countries within three days. However, it was not released in Japan until 10 December 2010.<ref name=IMDbReleaseDates/><ref name=\"japan-site\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robinhood-movie.jp/ |title=\u30ed\u30d3\u30f3\u30fb\u30d5\u30c3\u30c9\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Robin Hood'' was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray Disc]] on 20 September 2010 in the UK,<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Robin-Hood-Extended-Directors-Cut/dp/B003DZ131Y/ref=sr_1_2?s=dvd&ie=UTF8&qid=1359860713&sr=1-2 Amazon UK: ''Robin Hood \u2013 Extended Director's Cut (DVD)'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> and the following day in the US.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Robin-Hood-Single-Disc-Unrated-Directors/dp/B003U0AHBO/ref=sr_1_6?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1359860487&sr=1-6&keywords=robin+hood Amazon US: ''Robin Hood (Single-Disc Unrated Director's Cut) (2010)'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> While the UK home media releases only consisted of the extended 'Director's Cut' version (15 additional minutes), the US DVD and Blu-ray discs consisted of both the  'Director's Cut' version and the shorter theatrical version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kauffman|first=Jeffrey|title=Robin Hood Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Robin-Hood-Blu-ray/12967/#Review|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=15 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nOn its opening week, the film took \u00a35,750,332 in the UK, ahead of ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' and $36,063,385 in the US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenrush.co.uk/films/film-126127/box-office/ |title=Box-Office for the film (Robin Hood) |work=Screenrush |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref> and grossed a total of \u00a315,381,416 in the UK, $104,516,000 in the US and $321,669,741 worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nottingham.htm |title=Robin Hood (2010) |work=Box Office Mojo |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref>\nThe box-office figures were seen as somewhat of a disappointment, even though films set in\nmedieval times tend to fare poorly and ''Robin Hood'' actually ranks as the second highest-grossing medieval film in recent memory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3051&p=.htm |title='Gulliver,' 'Persia,' 'Narnia' Rank Among the Big Botches of 2010 |work=Box Office Mojo |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\nCritical reaction to ''Robin Hood'' has been mixed, with the film holding a 43% rating on review aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 245 reviews with an [[weighted mean|average]] rating of 5.34/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Ridley Scott's revisionist take on this oft-told tale offers some fine acting and a few gripping action sequences, but it's missing the thrill of adventure that made Robin Hood a legend in the first place.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/robin_hood_2010/ | title = Robin Hood Movie Reviews, Pictures | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref> Another review aggregator, [[Metacritic]], rates the film at 53% based on a [[Normalization (statistics)|normalised]] rating of 40 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web | url= http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/robinhood2010 | title = Robin Hood (2010): Reviews | work = [[Metacritic]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate= 13 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film two stars out of four, writing that \"little by little, title by title, innocence and joy is being drained out of the movies.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news |first=Roger|last=Ebert| authorlink = Roger Ebert | title= Merry Men N The Hood|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/robin-hood-2010|date=12 May 2010|via=rogerebert.com }} {{Rating|2|4}}</ref> Joe Neumaier of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' felt that \"the problem with Russell Crowe's new take on the legend is that it has one muddy boot in history and the other in fantasy. The middling result is far from a bull's-eye.\"<ref>{{cite news| date = 11 May 2010| first=Joe|last=Naumier | title = Robin Hood| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2010/05/11/2010-05-11_robin_hood_arrow_isnt_on_the_mark.html | work = [[New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|location=New York City}} {{Rating|3|5}}</ref> David Roark of ''[[RELEVANT (magazine)|Relevant]]'' accused Scott of replacing depth with detail and manipulative themes, like vengeance and unjust war, and stated that Scott had sucked the life out of a cherished fable, writing that \"Scott has turned a myth, a concept essentially, into a history which emerges as dry, insensible clutter.\"<ref name=\"Relevant Magazine\">{{cite web |first=David|last=Roark| url = http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/21555-robin-hood | title = Robin Hood\u2014Review | work = [[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]| publisher=Relevant Media|location=Winter Park, Florida|accessdate= 7 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAmong the film's more positive reviews, [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote that \"Scott has great command of his action sequences\" and praised his \"sophisticated approach to the material.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|authorlink=Mick LaSalle|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Review-Gritty-variation-on-Robin-Hood-3188972.php |title=Review: Gritty variation on 'Robin Hood'|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst]]|location=San Francisco, California|date=14 May 2010}}</ref> [[Ty Burr]] of the ''[[Boston Globe]]'' called the film \"smart, muscular entertainment\" and wrote that Crowe \"possesses a presence and authority to make you forget all about [[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves|Kevin Costner]].\"<ref>[http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2010/05/14/merry_men_with_muscle_in_robin_hood/ Robin Hood] Ty Burr, ''Boston Globe'', 14 May 2010</ref> [[Lou Lumenick]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called ''Robin Hood'' \"head and shoulders above the sort of lightheaded epics Hollywood typically offers during the summer season.\"<ref>[http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/lou_cannes_blog_at_nypost_com_cbPPSXwVtwZLjAPKGe1D3L 'Robin Hood' a sure shot!] Lou Lumenick, ''New York Post'', 14 May 2010</ref>\n\nRussell Crowe received criticism from the British media for his variable accent during the film. ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' said his accent was occasionally Scottish,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=134778 | first = Dan | last = Jolin | work = Empire | title=Reviews: Robin Hood | accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> while ''[[Total Film]]'' thought there were also times when it sounded Irish.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/robin-hood-1 | author = Andy Lowe | work=Total Film Magazine | title=Reviews: Robin Hood | accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> [[Mark Lawson]], while interviewing Crowe on [[BBC Radio 4]], suggested there were hints of Irish in his accent, which angered Crowe who described this as \"bollocks\" and stormed out.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/organgrinder/2010/may/14/russell-crowe-accent-acrimony | author=John Plunkett | work=The Guardian (blog) | title=Russell Crowe puts accent on acrimony | date=14 May 2010 | accessdate=14 May 2010| location=London}} (Includes audio file)</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00s8zd0 Russell Crowe, Ashes to Ashes and the Archbishop of Canterbury]</ref>\n\nA number of reviewers have criticised historical inaccuracies in the film. In ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[A. O. Scott]] complained that the film made \"a hash of the historical record\".<ref>{{Cite web | last=Scott | first=A. O. | authorlink=A. O. Scott | title=Rob the Rich? Give to the Poor? Oh, Puh-leeze! | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/05/14/movies/14robin.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=13 May 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2012 }}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alex von Tunzelmann]] complained that the film was filled with historical impossibilities and anachronisms. She notes that Richard the Lionheart was indeed fighting in France in 1199, but that he had actually come back from the Holy Land seven years earlier, so it is inaccurate to depict him fighting in France on his way back from the Holy Land in 1199, as is the case in the film.<ref>{{Cite web | last=Von Tunzelmann | first=Alex | authorlink=Alex von Tunzelmann | title=Reel history special: Ridley Scott's Robin Hood \u2013 wide of the mark? | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/sep/23/ridley-scott-robin-hood-russell-crowe | work=The Guardian | date=23 September 2010 | accessdate=26 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2011\n| [[People's Choice Award]]\n| [[People's Choice Award|Favourite Action Film]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture|Stunt Ensemble]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Action|Choice Movie: Action]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[9th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n|[[Visual Effects Society Award for Outstanding Supporting Visual Effects in a Feature Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Visual Effects in a Feature Motion Picture]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[37th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n|[[Saturn Award for Best Action or Adventure Film|Best Action/Adventure Film]]\n|{{nom}}\n\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack to ''Robin Hood'', with music written and performed by [[Marc Streitenfeld]], was released on 11 May 2010.\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = \n| total_length    = 51:39<ref>[http://www.theost.com/2010/robin_hood.html Robin Hood Soundtrack] TheOST. Retrieved 10 March 2014</ref>\n| title1          = Destiny\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = Creatures\n| length2         = 2:09\n| title3          = Fate Has Smiled Upon Us\n| length3         = 2:02\n| title4          = Godfrey\n| length4         = 3:32\n| title5          = Ambush\n| length5         = 1:16\n| title6          = Pact Sworn in blood\n| length6         = 2:52\n| title7          = Returning the Crown\n| length7         = 1:13\n| title8          = Planting the Fields\n| length8         = 1:18\n| title9          = Sherwood Forest\n| length9         = 2:19\n| title10         = John Is King\n| length10        = 4:02\n| title11         = Robin Speaks\n| length11        = 2:33\n| title12         = Killing Walter\n| length12        = 2:02\n| title13         = Nottingham Burns\n| length13        = 2:12\n| title14         = Siege\n| length14        = 2:11\n| title15         = Landing of the French\n| length15        = 2:49\n| title16         = Walter's Burial\n| length16        = 3:05\n| title17         = Preparing for Battle\n| length17        = 2:41\n| title18         = Charge\n| length18        = 1:20\n| title19         = Clash\n| length19        = 2:41\n| title20         = The Final Arrow\n| length20        = 2:30\n| title21         = The Legend Begins\n| length21        = 1:28\n| title22         = Merry Men\n| length22        = 1:48\n}}\n\n==Potential sequels==\nScott indicated he had been considering further films, in an interview with ''[[The Times]]'' on 4 April 2010, stating, \"Honestly, I thought why not have the potential for a sequel?\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article7082802.ece | location=London | work=The Times | first=Will | last=Lawrence | title=Behind the scenes of a brand new Robin Hood | date=4 April 2010}}{{subscription required}}</ref> and \"Let's say we might presume there's a sequel.\" At the world premiere in [[Cannes]], Crowe declared he was willing \"if I had the opportunity to address what happens next with Ridley and Cate, then great, let's do it.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE64A6N620100513?pageNumber=1 | agency=Reuters | title=\"Robin Hood\" opens Cannes, Crowe hints at sequel | date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|Film<!--For UK-->}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|0955308|Robin Hood}}\n* {{mojo title|nottingham|Robin Hood}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|robin_hood_2010|Robin Hood}}\n* {{metacritic film|robin-hood|Robin Hood}}\n\n{{Ridley Scott}}\n{{Robin Hood}}\n{{Brian Grazer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robin Hood 2010}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British action films]]\n[[Category:British epic films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Films about archery]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood films]]\n[[Category:Imagine Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Relativity Media films]]\n[[Category:Scott Free Productions films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ridley Scott]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brian Grazer]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Brian Helgeland]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Eleanor of Aquitaine]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Richard I of England]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John, King of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2010 adventure movie by Ridley Scott}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Robin Hood\n| image          = Robin Hood 2010 poster.jpg\n| alt            = <!-- see WP:ALT -->\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Ridley Scott]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Ridley Scott\n* [[Brian Grazer]]\n* Russell Crowe\n}}\n| screenplay     = [[Brian Helgeland]]\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* Brian Helgeland\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Ethan Reiff]]\n* [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Cyrus Voris]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Russell Crowe]]\n* [[Cate Blanchett]]\n* [[William Hurt]]\n* [[Mark Strong]]\n* [[Mark Addy]]\n* [[Oscar Isaac]]\n* [[Danny Huston]]\n* [[Eileen Atkins]]\n* [[Max von Sydow]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Marc Streitenfeld]]\n| cinematography = [[John Mathieson (cinematographer)|John Mathieson]]\n| editing        = [[Pietro Scalia]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Imagine Entertainment]]\n* [[Relativity Media]]\n* [[Scott Free Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|05|12|United Kingdom/Ireland|2010|05|14|North America|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 140 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2010/film/markets-festivals/robin-hood-1117942702/|title=Review: 'Robin Hood'|last=Chang|first=Justin|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=9 May 2010|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>\n| language       = English<br />French\n| budget         = $200 million<ref name=\"Fritz (2010)\">{{cite news |last=Fritz |first=Ben |title=''First Look: 'Robin Hood' wobbly in U.S. but hits target overseas'' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=16 May 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2010/05/robin-hood-wobbly-in-us-but-hits-target-overseas.html |accessdate= 12 September 2010}}</ref>\n| gross          = $321.7 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nottingham.htm | title=Robin Hood (2010) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=21 June 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Robin Hood''''' is a 2010 [[Epic film|epic]] [[Historical film|historical drama film]] based on the [[Robin Hood]] legend, directed by [[Ridley Scott]] and starring [[Russell Crowe]], [[Cate Blanchett]], [[William Hurt]], [[Mark Strong]], [[Mark Addy]], [[Oscar Isaac]], [[Danny Huston]], [[Eileen Atkins]], and [[Max von Sydow]]. It was released in 12 countries on 12 May 2010, including the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Ireland]] and was also the opening film at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]] the same day. It was released in a further 23 countries the following day, among them [[Australia]], and an additional 17 countries on 14 May 2010, among them the [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=IMDbReleaseDates>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0955308/releaseinfo IMDb: ''Release dates for Robin Hood'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> The film received mixed reviews and grossed $321.7 million against its $200 million budget, thus being considered a box office disappointment.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Anchor|Premise}}\nIn the year 1199, [[Robin Hood|Robin Longstride]] serves as a common [[archery|archer]] in the army of [[Richard I of England|King Richard the Lionheart]]. A veteran of [[Third Crusade|Richard's crusade]], he now takes part in the siege of [[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Chalus Castle]]. Disillusioned and war-weary, he gives a frank but unflattering appraisal of the King's conduct when the King asks his opinion, and Robin and his comrades\u2014archers [[Alan-a-Dale|Allan A'Dayle]] and [[Will Scarlett]] and soldier [[Little John]]\u2014find themselves in the [[stocks]].\n\nWhen the King is slain during an attack on the castle, Robin and his men decide to free themselves and desert. They come across an ambush of the English royal guard by Godfrey, an English knight who has conspired with [[Philip II of France|King Philip of France]] to assassinate King Richard. After chasing Godfrey away, Robin decides to take advantage of the situation by having his men impersonate the dead English knights to return to England. Before they depart to sail across the Channel, Robin promises one of the dying knights, Sir Robert Loxley, to return his sword to his father in [[Nottingham]].\n\nAwaking to find his party in the Thames estuary, Robin must continue to assume the identity of Loxley to inform the royal family of King Richard's death. He witnesses the coronation of [[John, King of England|King John]], who orders the collection of harsh new taxes and dispatches Godfrey to the [[Northern England|North]] to do so\u2014unaware that Godfrey will instead use French troops to stir up unrest and to prepare for King Philip to invade England.\n\nRobin and his companions head to Nottingham, where Loxley's elderly and blind father, Sir Walter, asks him to continue impersonating his son to prevent the Crown from seizing the Loxley family lands. Loxley's widow, [[Maid Marian|Lady Marian]], is initially cold toward Robin, but warms to him when he and his men merrily recover [[tithe]]d grain for the townsfolk to plant.\n\nGodfrey's actions incite the northern barons, who march to meet King John. Speaking now for Sir Walter, Robin proposes that King John agree to a [[Charter of the Forest|charter of rights]] to ensure the rights of every Englishman and to unite his country. Having realised Godfrey's deception, and knowing he must meet the French invasion with an army, the King agrees. Meanwhile, French marauders plunder Nottingham. Robin and the northern barons arrive to stop Godfrey's men, but not before Godfrey has slain the blind Sir Walter.\n\nAs the main French expeditionary force begins its invasion of England on a beach below the [[cliffs of Dover]], Robin leads the now united English army against them. In the midst of the battle, Robin duels with Godfrey, who attempts to kill Marian and flees until Robin finally kills him with an arrow from afar. King Philip realises that his plan to divide England has failed and calls off his invasion. When King John sees the French surrendering to Robin instead of to himself, he senses a threat to his power. In London, King John reneges on his promise to sign the charter and declares Robin an [[outlaw]] to be hunted throughout the kingdom. The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] announces the decree, and Robin and his men flee to [[Sherwood Forest]] with the orphans of Nottingham. Marian narrates their new life in the greenwood, noting that they live in equality as they right the many wrongs in the kingdom of King John. \"And so the legend begins.\"\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Russell Crowe]] as [[Robin Hood|Robin Longstride]]\n* [[Cate Blanchett]] as [[Maid Marian|Marian Loxley]]\n* [[William Hurt]] as [[William Marshal, 1st Earl of Pembroke|William Marshal]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Borys Kit |title=William Hurt jousting for Robin Hood role |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=12 April 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3iddc0608768893d1e82e7cae7eec09ccd |accessdate=13 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414080023/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3iddc0608768893d1e82e7cae7eec09ccd |archivedate=14 April 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Mark Strong]] as Sir Godfrey, Prince John's henchman\n* [[Mark Addy]] as [[Friar Tuck]]\n* [[Oscar Isaac]] as [[John, King of England|Prince John]], the younger brother of King Richard\n* [[Danny Huston]] as [[Richard I of England|King Richard the Lionheart]]\n* [[Eileen Atkins]] as [[Eleanor of Aquitaine]], King Richard and Prince John's mother\n* [[Max von Sydow]] as Sir Walter Loxley of Peper Harow\n* [[Kevin Durand]] as [[Little John]]<ref name=\"trio\">{{cite journal|first=Borys |last=Kit |title=Trio join Ridley Scott's Robin Hood film |journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=9 March 2009 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ia82652ffac56b32e4e4fe4b83a847fe8 |accessdate=10 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311043113/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3ia82652ffac56b32e4e4fe4b83a847fe8 |archivedate=11 March 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Scott Grimes]] as [[Will Scarlet]]\n* [[Matthew Macfadyen]] as the [[Sheriff of Nottingham]]<ref>{{cite news | author = Peter Sciretta | title = Ridley Scott Casts Matthew Macfadyen as The Sheriff of Nottingham in Robin Hood | work = SlashFilm | date = 24 April 2009 | url = http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/04/24/ridley-scott-casts-matthew-macfadyen-as-the-sheriff-of-nottingham-in-robin-hood/ | archive-url = https://archive.is/20120911055743/http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/04/24/ridley-scott-casts-matthew-macfadyen-as-the-sheriff-of-nottingham-in-robin-hood/ | url-status=dead | archive-date = 11 September 2012 | accessdate = 24 April 2009 }}</ref>\n* [[Alan Doyle]] as [[Alan-a-Dale|Allan A'Dayle]]<ref name=\"trio\" />\n* [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] as [[Isabella of Angoul\u00eame]], wife of Prince John and the French king's niece\n* [[Jonathan Zacca\u00ef]] as [[Philip II of France|King Philip of France]]\n* [[Douglas Hodge]] as Sir Robert Loxley\n* [[Robert Pugh]] as Baron Baldwin\n* [[Gerard McSorley]] as [[Walter Fitz Robert|Baron FitzRobert]]\n* [[Simon McBurney]] as Father Tancred \n* [[Mark Lewis Jones]] as Thomas Longstride, Robin's father\n* [[Denis Menochet]] as Adhemar, the aide to the French King\n* [[Jessica Raine]] as [[Isabel, Countess of Gloucester|Isabel of Gloucester]], John's first wife\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nIn January 2007, [[Universal Studios]] and [[Brian Grazer]]'s [[Imagine Entertainment]] acquired a [[spec script]] written by Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris, creators of the TV series ''[[Sleeper Cell (TV series)|Sleeper Cell]]''. Their script portrayed a more sympathetic [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] and less virtuous [[Robin Hood]], who becomes involved in a love triangle with [[Maid Marian|Lady Marian]]. The writers received a seven-figure deal for the purchase. Actor [[Russell Crowe]] was cast into the role of Robin Hood with a fee of $20&nbsp;million against 20% of the gross.<ref name=flies>{{cite journal | first=Michael | last=Fleming |author2=Diane Garrett | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117958414.html | title=Universal flies with Crowe | journal=Variety | date=31 January 2007 | accessdate=30 April 2007 }}</ref> The following April, [[Ridley Scott]] was hired to direct ''Nottingham''.<ref name=set>{{cite journal | first=Michael | last=Fleming | url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963977.html | title=Scott set for 'Nottingham' | journal=Variety | date=29 April 2007 | accessdate=30 April 2007 }}</ref> He had attempted to get rights for himself and [[20th Century Fox]], but had previously collaborated with Grazer on ''[[American Gangster (film)|American Gangster]]'' and signed on as director rather than producer.<ref name=\"romp\" /> Scott was not a fan of previous film versions of Robin Hood, saying \"the best, frankly, was [[Mel Brooks]]'s ''[[Robin Hood: Men in Tights|Men in Tights]]'', because [[Cary Elwes]] was quite a comic\".<ref name=\"cheese\">{{cite news|date=9 November 2008|first= Garth|last=Pearce|title= Russell Crowe to toughen up Robin Hood|work=[[The Times]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5114486.ece|quote=I am trying to think of the last good one,\" said Scott. \"Errol Flynn? A bit cheesy? A big cheese. God bless him. Kevin Costner? In the wig, you mean? The one I thought was the best, frankly, was Mel Brooks's Men in Tights, because Cary Elwes [who played Robin] was quite a comic. <!-- quote needed, link very likely to become unavailable -->| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5q2qBqXSq?url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5114486.ece|archivedate=27 May 2010|accessdate=11 November 2008|url-status=dead|location=London}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nScott's dissatisfaction with the script led him to delay filming, and during 2008 it was rewritten into a story about Robin Hood becoming an outlaw; at one point Crowe was even being considered for a dual role as both Robin and the Sheriff. Scott dropped the latter notion and ''Nottingham'' was retitled to reflect the more traditional angle.\n\nIn June, screenwriter [[Brian Helgeland]] was hired to rewrite the script by Reiff and Voris.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Borys|last=Kit|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i07e0f44f77790770427fb5561f94cf24|title=Helgeland new sheriff of 'Nottingham'|journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=5 June 2007|accessdate=5 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607164119/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i07e0f44f77790770427fb5561f94cf24 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=7 June 2007}}</ref> Producer Marc Shmuger explained Scott had a different interpretation of the story from \"the script, [which] had the sheriff of Nottingham as a ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]''-style forensics investigator\".<ref name=\"romp\">{{cite news|first=Patrick|last=Goldstein|title='Nottingham': Will Russell Crowe ever romp in Sherwood Forest?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=7 August 2008|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2008/08/nottingham-will.html|accessdate=7 August 2008}}</ref> Scott elaborated the script, portraying the Sheriff of Nottingham as being [[Richard I of England|Richard the Lionheart]]'s right-hand man, who returns to England to serve [[John of England|Prince John]] after Richard's assassination. Though Scott felt John \"was actually pretty smart, he got a bad rap because he introduced taxation so he's the bad guy in this\", and the Sheriff would have been torn between the \"two wrongs\" of a corrupt king and an outlaw inciting anarchy.<ref>{{cite news | first=Shawn | last=Adler | url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2007/10/22/grazer-calls-scotts-nottingham-the-gladiator-of-robin-hood-movies/ | title=Grazer Calls Scott's 'Nottingham' The 'Gladiator' of Robin Hood Movies | work=MTV Movies Blog | date=22 October 2007 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref> Locations were sought in North East England including [[Alnwick Castle]], [[Bamburgh Castle]], and [[Kielder Forest]]. A portion of filming was intended to take place in [[Northumberland]]. As a result of the [[2007\u20132008 Writers Guild of America strike|WGA strike]], production was put on hold.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/Sir-Ridley-Scott-puts-big.3662334.jp | title=Sir Ridley Scott puts big budget movie on hold | work=[[Shields Gazette]] | publisher=[[Johnston Press]] | date=10 January 2008 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref> Scott sought to begin production in 2008 for a release in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | first=Lawrie | last=Masterson | url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,23005986-5009160,00.html | title=An alliance to Crowe about | work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | date=5 January 2008 | accessdate=29 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFilming was scheduled to begin in August in [[Sherwood Forest]] if the [[2008 Screen Actors Guild strike]] did not take place,<ref>{{cite news | first = Claudia | last = Eller |author2=Richard Verrier  | title = Strike threat creates a suspense drama for Hollywood | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 24 June 2008 | url = http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-actor24-2008jun24,0,4147025.story | accessdate=24 June 2008}}</ref> for release on 26 November 2009. By July, filming was delayed,<ref>{{cite journal | first=Gregg | last=Kilday | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3if7b717939831cbe23d5f5d7875615784 | title=Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham' hits delay | journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=27 July 2008 | accessdate=26 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080727135443/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3if7b717939831cbe23d5f5d7875615784 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 July 2008}}</ref> and playwright Paul Webb was hired to rewrite the script.<ref name=\"romp\" /> The film was moved to 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|title='Wolfman,' 'Nottingham' delayed|journal=Variety|date=10 December 2008|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997153.html |accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref> The Sheriff of Nottingham's character was then merged with Robin.<ref>{{cite news|first=Josh|last=Horowitz|title=BREAKING: Russell Crowe Will Play Robin Hood AND The Sheriff In Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham'|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=27 September 2008|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/09/27/breaking-russell-crowe-will-play-robin-hood-and-the-sheriff-in-ridley-scotts-nottingham/|accessdate=28 September 2008}}</ref> Scott explained Robin \"has to retire to the forest to resume his name Robin. So he was momentarily the Sheriff of Nottingham.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Simon|last=Reynolds|title=\nScott explains Crowe's 'Nottingham' role|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=11 November 2008|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/a135277/scott-explains-crowes-nottingham-role.html|accessdate=11 November 2008}}</ref> Hedgeland returned to rewrite, adding an opening where Robin witnesses the Sheriff dying in battle, and takes over his identity.<ref name=\"confusion\">{{cite news|first=Josh|last=Horowitz|title=Brian Grazer Reveals 'Nottingham' Plot Points, Sets Record Straight on Russell Crowe Confusion|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=1 December 2008|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2008/12/01/brian-grazer-reveals-nottingham-plot-points-sets-record-straight-on-russell-crowe-confusion/|accessdate=1 December 2008}}</ref> Scott chose to begin filming in February 2009 in forests around London, having discovered many trees which had not been [[pollarding|pollarded]].<ref name=\"cheese\" /> Scott was also pleased that the {{convert|200|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[Nottinghamshire]] set that was built during 2008 had aged into the landscape.<ref>{{cite news|first=Christine|last=Sams|title=An epic of merrymen|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=1 February 2009}}</ref> By February 2009, Scott revealed ''Nottingham'' had become his version of ''Robin Hood'', as he had become dissatisfied with the idea of Robin starting as the Sheriff.<ref name=\"french\">{{cite news|url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/02/17/exclusive-ridley-scott-reveals-new-name-for-nottingham-and-its-back-to-basics/|title=Ridley Scott Reveals New Name For 'Nottingham' And It's Back To Basics|work=MTV Movies Blog|date=17 February 2009|first=Larry|last=Carroll|accessdate=17 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n| title = Filming locations\n| lines = 5\n| width = 250\n|File:Bourne Wood Movie Castle.jpg|alt1=Mock castle at the Bourne Wood at the end of filming, showing the burnt-out castle gate|Mock castle ([[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Castle Chalus]] in the film) at [[Bourne Wood]] at the end of filming, showing the burnt-out castle gate, Bourne Wood, Farnham, Surrey, 8 August 2009. {{coord|51|11|26.31|N|0|46|39.01|W|region:GB_scale:5000|display=inline}}\n|File:Bourne Wood Castle Gate.JPG|alt2=Burnt out castle gate and battering ram|Burnt out gate of mock castle and battering ram (nicknamed 'Rosie'), [[Bourne Wood]], Farnham, Surrey, 8 August 2009.\n|File:Robin Hood filming at Freshwater West.jpg|alt3=Filming the fight scenes on the beach|Filming the fight scenes on the beach, Freshwater West, Pembrokeshire, Wales, 23 June 2009. {{coord|51|39|31.90|N|5|3|52.23|W|region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline}}\n|File:Robin Hood filming at Freshwater West 2.jpg|alt4=The beach filming|The beach filming, Freshwater West, Pembrokeshire, Wales, 23 June 2009.\n}}\nFilming began on 30 March 2009.<ref name=\"pressrelease\">{{cite news|title=Ridley Scott's Robin Hood film begins production|work=In Contention|format=Press release|date=24 March 2009|url=http://www.incontention.com/?p=4917|accessdate=24 March 2009}}</ref> In June and July, the crew filmed at [[Freshwater West]], in [[Pembrokeshire]], Wales.<ref>{{cite news|title=Extras queue for Robin Hood roles|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=9 May 2009|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8041103.stm|accessdate=10 May 2009}}</ref> The arrival of the dead king's cog (boat), accompanied by Robin and his men, at the Tower of London was filmed at Virginia Water, where a partial mock-up of the Tower was built. Extensive scenes from the film were filmed on the [[Ashridge Estate]], [[Little Gaddesden]], on the [[Hertfordshire]]/[[Buckinghamshire]] border.<ref>{{cite news|title=How the National Trust came to the aid of Robin Hood |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] |date=9 May 2009 |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-news/w-latest_news/w-news-how-the-national-trust-came-to-the-aid-of-robin-hood.htm |accessdate=10 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222033551/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-news/w-latest_news/w-news-how-the-national-trust-came-to-the-aid-of-robin-hood.htm |archivedate=22 February 2010 }}</ref> Filming of the siege of [[Ch\u00e2teau de Ch\u00e2lus-Chabrol|Castle Chalus]] took place at the [[Bourne Wood]] at [[Farnham]], Surrey during July and August.<ref name=SurreyLife>{{cite web | title=Surrey Film Locations | url=http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/surrey-film-locations-2505/ | work=Surrey Life | accessdate=1 June 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226070622/http://surrey.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/surrey-film-locations-2505/ | archivedate=26 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Filming also took place at [[Dovedale]] near [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Russell Crowe in Ashbourne|publisher=BBC Derby|date=5 August 2009|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/derby/content/articles/2009/08/05/russell_crowe_in_ashbourne_2009_feature.shtml|accessdate=5 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[battering ram]] used during the filming at the Bourne Wood in Surrey, which was nicknamed 'Rosie' by the film crew and is worth [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]60,000, was donated by Russell Crowe to a [[Scotland|Scottish]] charity, the [[The Clanranald Trust for Scotland|Clanranald Trust]] to be used for battle re-enactments at a fort named [[Duncarron]], built in a forest near the [[Carron Valley Reservoir]] in [[North Lanarkshire]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Charlie|first=Allan|title=Russell Crowe Helps a friend with a cause|url=http://www.clanranald.org/cln1/the-news/31-duncarron-news/111-russell-crowe-helps-a-friend-with-a-cause|publisher=The Clanranald Trust website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019154730/http://www.clanranald.org/cln1/the-news/31-duncarron-news/111-russell-crowe-helps-a-friend-with-a-cause|archivedate=19 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen interviewed in November 2008, Strong stated his character of Sir Godfrey was originally called Conrad and was based on [[Guy of Gisbourne]]. He described the original character as having blond hair and a disfigurement from being struck by a crossbow bolt.<ref>{{cite web | first = Simon | last = Reynolds | title = Strong joins Ridley Scott's 'Nottingham' | work = [[Digital Spy]] | date = 10 November 2008 | url = http://fame.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/a135178/strong-joins-ridley-scotts-nottingham.html | accessdate = 11 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on 12 May 2010 in 12 countries, including the United Kingdom and Ireland, and was also the opening film at the [[2010 Cannes Film Festival]] the same day. It was released in a further 23 countries the following day, among them Australia, and an additional 17 countries on 14 May 2010, among them the United States and Canada. It was thus released in 52 countries within three days. However, it was not released in Japan until 10 December 2010.<ref name=IMDbReleaseDates/><ref name=\"japan-site\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robinhood-movie.jp/ |title=\u30ed\u30d3\u30f3\u30fb\u30d5\u30c3\u30c9\u516c\u5f0f\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Robin Hood'' was released on DVD and [[Blu-ray Disc]] on 20 September 2010 in the UK,<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Robin-Hood-Extended-Directors-Cut/dp/B003DZ131Y/ref=sr_1_2?s=dvd&ie=UTF8&qid=1359860713&sr=1-2 Amazon UK: ''Robin Hood \u2013 Extended Director's Cut (DVD)'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> and the following day in the US.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Robin-Hood-Single-Disc-Unrated-Directors/dp/B003U0AHBO/ref=sr_1_6?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1359860487&sr=1-6&keywords=robin+hood Amazon US: ''Robin Hood (Single-Disc Unrated Director's Cut) (2010)'']. Retrieved 3 February 2013</ref> While the UK home media releases only consisted of the extended 'Director's Cut' version (15 additional minutes), the US DVD and Blu-ray discs consisted of both the  'Director's Cut' version and the shorter theatrical version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kauffman|first=Jeffrey|title=Robin Hood Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Robin-Hood-Blu-ray/12967/#Review|publisher=Blu-ray.com|accessdate=1 October 2012|date=15 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nOn its opening week, the film took \u00a35,750,332 in the UK, ahead of ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' and $36,063,385 in the US,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenrush.co.uk/films/film-126127/box-office/ |title=Box-Office for the film (Robin Hood) |work=Screenrush |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref> and grossed a total of \u00a315,381,416 in the UK, $104,516,000 in the US and $321,669,741 worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=nottingham.htm |title=Robin Hood (2010) |work=Box Office Mojo |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref>\nThe box-office figures were seen as somewhat of a disappointment, even though films set in\nmedieval times tend to fare poorly and ''Robin Hood'' actually ranks as the second highest-grossing medieval film in recent memory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3051&p=.htm |title='Gulliver,' 'Persia,' 'Narnia' Rank Among the Big Botches of 2010 |work=Box Office Mojo |date=20 January 2011 |accessdate=10 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Anchor|Critics}}\nCritical reaction to ''Robin Hood'' has been mixed, with the film holding a 43% rating on review aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 245 reviews with an [[weighted mean|average]] rating of 5.34/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"Ridley Scott's revisionist take on this oft-told tale offers some fine acting and a few gripping action sequences, but it's missing the thrill of adventure that made Robin Hood a legend in the first place.\"<ref name=\"tomatoes\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/robin_hood_2010/ | title = Robin Hood Movie Reviews, Pictures | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref> Another review aggregator, [[Metacritic]], rates the film at 53% based on a [[Normalization (statistics)|normalised]] rating of 40 reviews.<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web | url= http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/robinhood2010 | title = Robin Hood (2010): Reviews | work = [[Metacritic]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate= 13 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film two stars out of four, writing that \"little by little, title by title, innocence and joy is being drained out of the movies.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news |first=Roger|last=Ebert| authorlink = Roger Ebert | title= Merry Men N The Hood|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|location=Chicago, Illinois|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/robin-hood-2010|date=May 12, 2010|via=rogerebert.com }} {{Rating|2|4}}</ref> Joe Neumaier of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' felt that \"the problem with Russell Crowe's new take on the legend is that it has one muddy boot in history and the other in fantasy. The middling result is far from a bull's-eye.\"<ref>{{cite news| date = May 11, 2010| first=Joe|last=Naumier | title = Robin Hood| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2010/05/11/2010-05-11_robin_hood_arrow_isnt_on_the_mark.html | work = [[New York Daily News]]|publisher=[[Tribune Publishing]]|location=New York City}} {{Rating|3|5}}</ref> David Roark of ''[[RELEVANT (magazine)|Relevant]]'' accused Scott of replacing depth with detail and manipulative themes, like vengeance and unjust war, and stated that Scott had sucked the life out of a cherished fable, writing that \"Scott has turned a myth, a concept essentially, into a history which emerges as dry, insensible clutter.\"<ref name=\"Relevant Magazine\">{{cite web |first=David|last=Roark| url = http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/21555-robin-hood | title = Robin Hood\u2014Review | work = [[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]| publisher=Relevant Media|location=Winter Park, Florida|accessdate= 7 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAmong the film's more positive reviews, [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' wrote that \"Scott has great command of his action sequences\" and praised his \"sophisticated approach to the material.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mick|last=LaSalle|authorlink=Mick LaSalle|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Review-Gritty-variation-on-Robin-Hood-3188972.php |title=Review: Gritty variation on 'Robin Hood'|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst]]|location=San Francisco, California|date=May 14, 2010}}</ref> [[Ty Burr]] of the ''[[Boston Globe]]'' called the film \"smart, muscular entertainment\" and wrote that Crowe \"possesses a presence and authority to make you forget all about [[Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves|Kevin Costner]].\"<ref>[http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2010/05/14/merry_men_with_muscle_in_robin_hood/ Robin Hood] Ty Burr, ''Boston Globe'', 14 May 2010</ref> [[Lou Lumenick]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called ''Robin Hood'' \"head and shoulders above the sort of lightheaded epics Hollywood typically offers during the summer season.\"<ref>[http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/lou_cannes_blog_at_nypost_com_cbPPSXwVtwZLjAPKGe1D3L 'Robin Hood' a sure shot!] Lou Lumenick, ''New York Post'', 14 May 2010</ref>\n\nRussell Crowe received criticism from the British media for his variable accent during the film. ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' said his accent was occasionally Scottish,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=134778 | first = Dan | last = Jolin | work = Empire | title=Reviews: Robin Hood | accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> while ''[[Total Film]]'' thought there were also times when it sounded Irish.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/cinema/robin-hood-1 | author = Andy Lowe | work=Total Film Magazine | title=Reviews: Robin Hood | accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> [[Mark Lawson]], while interviewing Crowe on [[BBC Radio 4]], suggested there were hints of Irish in his accent, which angered Crowe who described this as \"bollocks\" and stormed out.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/organgrinder/2010/may/14/russell-crowe-accent-acrimony | author=John Plunkett | work=The Guardian (blog) | title=Russell Crowe puts accent on acrimony | date=14 May 2010 | accessdate=14 May 2010| location=London}} (Includes audio file)</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00s8zd0 Russell Crowe, Ashes to Ashes and the Archbishop of Canterbury]</ref>\n\nA number of reviewers have criticised historical inaccuracies in the film. In ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[A. O. Scott]] complained that the film made \"a hash of the historical record\".<ref>{{Cite web | last=Scott | first=A. O. | authorlink=A. O. Scott | title=Rob the Rich? Give to the Poor? Oh, Puh-leeze! | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2010/05/14/movies/14robin.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=13 May 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2012 }}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alex von Tunzelmann]] complained that the film was filled with historical impossibilities and anachronisms. She notes that Richard the Lionheart was indeed fighting in France in 1199, but that he had actually come back from the Holy Land seven years earlier, so it is inaccurate to depict him fighting in France on his way back from the Holy Land in 1199, as is the case in the film.<ref>{{Cite web | last=Von Tunzelmann | first=Alex | authorlink=Alex von Tunzelmann | title=Reel history special: Ridley Scott's Robin Hood \u2013 wide of the mark? | url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/sep/23/ridley-scott-robin-hood-russell-crowe | work=The Guardian | date=23 September 2010 | accessdate=26 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2011\n| [[People's Choice Award]]\n| [[People's Choice Award|Favourite Action Film]]\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Motion Picture|Stunt Ensemble]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|[[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Action|Choice Movie: Action]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[9th Visual Effects Society Awards|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n|[[Visual Effects Society Award for Outstanding Supporting Visual Effects in a Feature Motion Picture|Outstanding Supporting Visual Effects in a Feature Motion Picture]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[37th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n|[[Saturn Award for Best Action or Adventure Film|Best Action/Adventure Film]]\n|{{nom}}\n\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe soundtrack to ''Robin Hood'', with music written and performed by [[Marc Streitenfeld]], was released on 11 May 2010.\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = \n| total_length    = 51:39<ref>[http://www.theost.com/2010/robin_hood.html Robin Hood Soundtrack] TheOST. Retrieved 10 March 2014</ref>\n| title1          = Destiny\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = Creatures\n| length2         = 2:09\n| title3          = Fate Has Smiled Upon Us\n| length3         = 2:02\n| title4          = Godfrey\n| length4         = 3:32\n| title5          = Ambush\n| length5         = 1:16\n| title6          = Pact Sworn in blood\n| length6         = 2:52\n| title7          = Returning the Crown\n| length7         = 1:13\n| title8          = Planting the Fields\n| length8         = 1:18\n| title9          = Sherwood Forest\n| length9         = 2:19\n| title10         = John Is King\n| length10        = 4:02\n| title11         = Robin Speaks\n| length11        = 2:33\n| title12         = Killing Walter\n| length12        = 2:02\n| title13         = Nottingham Burns\n| length13        = 2:12\n| title14         = Siege\n| length14        = 2:11\n| title15         = Landing of the French\n| length15        = 2:49\n| title16         = Walter's Burial\n| length16        = 3:05\n| title17         = Preparing for Battle\n| length17        = 2:41\n| title18         = Charge\n| length18        = 1:20\n| title19         = Clash\n| length19        = 2:41\n| title20         = The Final Arrow\n| length20        = 2:30\n| title21         = The Legend Begins\n| length21        = 1:28\n| title22         = Merry Men\n| length22        = 1:48\n}}\n\n==Potential sequels==\nScott indicated he had been considering further films, in an interview with ''[[The Times]]'' on 4 April 2010, stating, \"Honestly, I thought why not have the potential for a sequel?\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article7082802.ece | location=London | work=The Times | first=Will | last=Lawrence | title=Behind the scenes of a brand new Robin Hood | date=4 April 2010}}{{subscription required}}</ref> and \"Let's say we might presume there's a sequel.\" At the world premiere in [[Cannes]], Crowe declared he was willing \"if I had the opportunity to address what happens next with Ridley and Cate, then great, let's do it.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTRE64A6N620100513?pageNumber=1 | agency=Reuters | title=\"Robin Hood\" opens Cannes, Crowe hints at sequel | date=13 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Film|United States|Film<!--For UK-->}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|0955308|Robin Hood}}\n* {{mojo title|nottingham|Robin Hood}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|robin_hood_2010|Robin Hood}}\n* {{metacritic film|robin-hood|Robin Hood}}\n\n{{Ridley Scott}}\n{{Robin Hood}}\n{{Brian Grazer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robin Hood 2010}}\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British action films]]\n[[Category:British epic films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Films about archery]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood films]]\n[[Category:Imagine Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Relativity Media films]]\n[[Category:Scott Free Productions films]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ridley Scott]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brian Grazer]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Brian Helgeland]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Eleanor of Aquitaine]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Richard I of England]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of John, King of England]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robin_Hood_(2010_film)"}
